<Overview>
    <FormattedContent><![CDATA[

<h1>Welcome to the qualification task for food image segmentation!</h1>

This is a research project of the <a href="https://www.digitalepidemiologylab.org" target="_blank">Digital Epidemiology Lab</a> of the Swiss Federal Institute of Technology in Lausanne/Geneva!
We are training computer vision models to identify different food items, and <b>we need your help to get good training data!</b>
Please read these instructions carefully and take a very short quiz before starting to help us with our HITs!

<h2>Instructions for the task</h2>
<ul>
    <li>In the task, you will use the tracing tool to draw a shape around each instance of the indicated food item(s) ("pizza" for example).</li>
    <li>If you're not sure what the item is, please use the search tool to look at example images.
        If the item is not present in the image, click the <b>No matching item(s) in this image</b> button to flag it.
    </li>
    <li>
        You should usually trace each instance of the indicated item separately,
        but if you see more than 10 instances clustered together (for example a bunch of grapes)
        then trace around that entire region.
    </li>
    <li>Your shapes should closely follow the object boundaries, so use the <b>Zoom</b> button if needed!</li>
    <li><b>Please do not include tableware (bowls, plates, forks, etc.).</b></li>
</ul>

<h2>Good examples</h2>
<ul>
    <li>
        This segmentation is good because the grapes should be considered as one contiguous region.
        <img alt="grapes" src="https://s3.eu-central-1.amazonaws.com/myfoodrepo-bing-images/static_qualification/bunch_of_grapes.png" height="200" />
    </li>
    <li>
        This segmentation is good because each cookie is traced separately.
        <img alt="cookies" src="https://s3.eu-central-1.amazonaws.com/myfoodrepo-bing-images/static_qualification/cookies_separate.png" height="200" />
    </li>
</ul>


<h2>Bad examples that will be rejected</h2>
<ul>
    <li>
        This user did not closely follow the object boundary.
        <img alt="sloppy tracing" src="https://s3.eu-central-1.amazonaws.com/myfoodrepo-bing-images/static_qualification/sloppy_tracing.png" height="200" />
    </li>
    <li>
        This user only traced one <b>pizza</b> of the two that appear in the image.
        <img alt="missing instance" src="https://s3.eu-central-1.amazonaws.com/myfoodrepo-bing-images/static_qualification/missing_instance.png" height="200" />
    </li>
    <li>
        This segmentation for <b>veal</b> included the other food items on the plate,
        and each of the three pieces of meat should be traced separately.
        <img alt="includes wrong food items" src="https://s3.eu-central-1.amazonaws.com/myfoodrepo-bing-images/static_qualification/includes_extraneous_foods_and_not_split.png" height="200" />
    </li>
</ul>

<h2>Please complete this short quiz (2 multiple-choice questions) to qualify for our food tracing tasks</h2>

    ]]></FormattedContent>
</Overview>

